# Steven Christopher — UI Vibe Rules

Mood anchor: cinematic, nocturnal, minimal, emotionally unresolved. *Designed,
not templated.* *Futuristic and retro at the same time.* If a change makes the
site feel like an app, a SaaS landing page, an influencer site, or a
Squarespace / Webflow theme — it is wrong.

> Steven, 2026-05-20: *"I want it to feel curated and designed, not like a
> template. Special and minimal."*

## North-star checks before shipping any change

1. Could this appear unedited on someone else's artist site? If yes, redesign.
2. Does every element on the page look like a deliberate choice? If anything
   feels default, replace it.
3. Does the page hold the *futuristic + retro* tension, or does it lean fully
   into one and become kitsch?

## Color

- Monochromatic. Commit fully to *light* or *dark*; never split the difference.
- Light surfaces: paper-bright off-white, not warm cream.
- Dark surfaces: ink-black, not dim "dark-mode" gray.
- Charcoal and washed gray are supporting tones only.
- Accents (sparingly, one per surface): deep muted red, desaturated navy,
  faded steel blue.
- Low saturation. No neon. No high-contrast brights.
- Texture, composition, and type weight matter more than color.

## Typography

- Primary voice: a real **monospace** (e.g. JetBrains Mono, IBM Plex Mono,
  GT America Mono, Söhne Mono). Mono carries the futuristic-and-retro tone.
- Supporting voice: a **stark geometric sans** (e.g. Söhne, Suisse Int'l,
  GT America, Inter Tight). Use for body and captions.
- Serifs are allowed only if **stark and structural** (IBM Plex Serif,
  Söhne Schmal, modernist slabs). Never decorative, romantic, or italic-display.
- Hard ban: rounded / soft / humanist serifs, italic display serifs, scripty
  faces, glitch/sci-fi pastiche, default system stacks in production.
- Never mix more than two families on a single surface.
- Type supports the mood; it never dominates — but it must always look
  *authored.*

> Steven rejected both decorative serifs we tried as *"too rounded, too soft"*
> and *"squirly squiggly round."* Do not reintroduce them.

## Layout & motion

- Negative space is the layout.
- Slow, intentional transitions. No springy, bouncy, or attention-grabbing
  motion.
- No scroll-jacking. No aggressive parallax.
- Hero areas: full-bleed image or video, sparse text. *One* focal subject.
- Reference patterns:
  [whatszep.com](https://www.whatszep.com/) (one-page, strong hero, links out),
  [beyonce.com](https://beyonce.com/) (minimal nav, single focal asset).
- Navigation: `Music`, `Video`, `Contact`. Keep it minimal.

## No about / origin / bio sections

Hard rule. Steven, twice unprompted: *"Don't need the origin/brand stuff —
cut out. People know what they're coming for."*

- No "About" / "Origin" / "Based in" / "Discipline" / "Field Note" / "Bio"
  blocks anywhere on the homepage.
- The music, video, and imagery do the explaining.
- If press copy must exist, it lives on a dedicated press page, not the home.

## Device priority — mobile-first, always

- ~99% of traffic is mobile. Design, build, and review every layout at ~375px
  width first. Desktop is the upscale, not the source of truth.
- `:hover` is a progressive enhancement only. Never gate critical information,
  state changes, navigation, or affordances behind hover-only reveals — every
  hover effect must have an equivalent always-visible or tap-driven state that
  works on touch.
- No hover-triggered tooltips, captions, or labels as the sole way to convey
  meaning. If a desktop interaction wouldn't survive on an iPhone, redesign it.

## Forever-new catalog — no release dates on music or video

- Never render release dates, drop dates, "year" labels, "released" pills, or
  any month/year metadata on music releases or music videos. The catalog must
  feel timeless and current; visible gaps between releases break the spell.
- Sorting collections by `releaseDate` internally is fine; rendering the value
  in the UI is not. The same rule applies to videos (`data.date`).
- Allowed date usage: footer copyright year, press article publication dates.
  Music + video items show format/type and title only — nothing time-stamped.

## Copy

- Minimal, selective, emotionally restrained.
- One line beats a paragraph. Never desperate, performatively edgy, sentimental,
  or over-explanatory.
- No marketing-speak, no exclamation marks, no emoji.

## Reject these patterns

- Hero with headline + subhead + CTA stack (SaaS pattern, never artist)
- Three-column "Music / About / Contact" feature rows
- "As featured in" logo strips
- Decorative section dividers, "scroll to explore" prompts, numbered step
  indicators that only fill space
- Glossy pop aesthetics, influencer styling, heavy retouching
- Bright commercial lighting in imagery
- Dashboard / startup / SaaS visual language
- Dense UI, busy layouts, CTA-stacked sections
- Decorative gradients, drop shadows for "depth", glassmorphism
- Generic stock photography
- Anything that reads as a Squarespace, Webflow, or Wix theme

